==English==

===Alternative spellings===
*[[-e]]
*[[-y]]

===Etymology 1===
From Old English '''[[-ig]]''', from Germanic

====Suffix====
'''-y'''

# Added to nouns and adjectives to form adjectives meaning 'having the quality of'
#: mess, [[messy]]
#: mouse, [[mousey]], [[mousy]]
# Added to verbs to form adjectives meaning '[[incline]]d to'
#: [[runny]]
#: [[sticky]]

====Translations====
''Note: translations of English words ending in '''-y''' do not necessarily end in the suffixes listed below.''
{{top}}
*Finnish: [[-inen#Finnish|-inen]] (1), [[-va#Finnish|-va]] (2), [[-vä#Finnish|-vä]] (2)
{{mid}}
*French: [[-eux]] {{m}}, [[-euse]] {{f}}
*Italian: [[-oso]] {{m}}, [[-osa]] {{f}}
{{bottom}}

===Etymology 2===
From Middle English, originally [[Scots]]

====Suffix====
'''-y'''

# Forming [[diminutive]] nouns
#: [[granny]]
#: Dicky

====Translations====
''Note: translations of English words ending in '''-y''' do not necessarily end in the suffixes listed below.''
{{top}}
*Finnish: [[-nen#Finnish|-nen]]
*French: [[-et]], [[-ette]], [[-ine]]
{{mid}}
*Italian: [[-etto]] {{m}}, -etta {{f}}, [[-ino]] {{m}}, -ina {{f}}
*Spanish: [[-ito]] {{m}}, [[-ita]] {{f}}, [[-iño]] {{m}}, [[-iña]] {{f}}
{{bottom}}

===Etymology 3===
From French ''-ie'' and ''-e'', from Latin ''-ia'', ''-ium'', ''[[-tas]]'', Greek ''-eia'', ''-ia''

====Suffix====
'''-y'''

# Forming nouns denoting a state, condition, or quality
# modest, [[modestas]], [[modesty]]  <!-- not a good example of -ia -->
# honest, honesty

====Translations====
''Note: translations of English words ending in '''-y''' do not necessarily end in the suffixes listed below.''
{{top}}
*Finnish: [[-uus#Finnish|-uus]], [[-yys#Finnish|-yys]]
{{mid}}
*French: [[-é]]
*Italian: [[-à]]
{{bottom}}

